  footnotes:
  - key: '[주-D001] 장이(丈二)의 인끈 : '
    value: 《한서》를 보면, “장이의 인끈으로 방외를 진무한다.”라는 말이 있다. 장이는 일장 이척(一丈二尺) 길이의 인끈이다.
  - key: '[주-D002] 척일(尺一)의 조서 : '
    value: 조서(詔書)를 척일서(尺一書)라 한다. 한(漢)나라 때에 조서를 쓰는데 한 자 한 치의 목판(木版)에 썼기 때문이라 한다.
  - key: '[주-D003] 의발(衣鉢) : '
    value: 학문의 법통을 전하는 것을 의발(衣鉢)을 전한다고 한다. 즉 불가(佛家)에서 중이 죽으면 입던 가사(袈裟)와 반발(飯鉢)을 후배에게 전해 준다는 것에서 나온 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D004] 감당(甘棠)의 교화 : '
    value: 주(周)나라 방백(方伯)으로 있던 소공(召公)이 향읍(鄕邑)을 순회할 때 감당나무 밑에서 쉬면서 백성을 교화하니, 백성들이 그 덕을 사모하여 그 나무를 길이 보호하였다.
  - key: '[주-D005] 봉래(蓬萊)의 …… 자리 : '
    value: 당나라 궁전으로 봉래궁(蓬萊宮)이 있었다. 청절(淸切)은 맑고 엄중한 곳이란 말이다.
  - key: '[주-D006] 주(朱)와 …… 구분하니 : '
    value: 주필(朱筆)과 묵필(墨筆)을 가지고 장부를 정리하는 것을 말한다. 즉, 관청에서 집무(執務)하는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D007] 일왕(一王)의 법 : '
    value: 한나라의 왕조(王朝)에서 시행한 제도이다.
  - key: '[주-D008] 푸른 …… 탔고 : '
    value: 지방장관이 되어 백성에게 왕의 교화를 펴는 것이다.
  - key: '[주-D009] 자미화(紫微花) …… 잡았다 : '
    value: 옛날 사관(史官)이 임금의 좌우에 있었는데, 좌사(左史)는 일을 기록하고, 우사(右史)는 말을 기록했다.
  - key: '[주-D010] 인국(麟局)에서 …… 닦고 : '
    value: 사국(史局)을 인국(麟局)이라 한다. 공자(孔子)가 춘추(春秋)를 지을 때 획인(獲麟)에서 절필(絶筆)하였기 때문에 수사(修史)하는 곳을 인국이라 하고, 미목의 편은 사실대로 기록하는 역사를 말한다. 사람의 미목(眉目) 그대로 그리 듯한다는 뜻이다.
  - key: '[주-D011] 학무(鶴舞)에서 …… 토하였다. : '
    value: 태자(太子)의 궁을 학금(鶴禁)이라 함과 같이 태자 궁안을 말하는 것이고, 심간의 비단은 문장의 재주가 풍부함을 말한다.
english:
  title: Proclamation of Appointment
  author: Lee Chang-yong
  language: eng
  text: |-
    The golden seal does not rest upon the ordinary, and the jade handle must be sought among the great in reputation. When talent presents itself, it rises to prominence; and when one ascends to the cap and robes of office, the opening of one's heart waters mine, bringing forth the blessings of wind and cloud. I proclaim this magnificent mandate to all the luminous court.

    Official Park Mun-sung possesses an expansive nature and radiant bearing. Born of generations of noble families, his talents flourish; inheriting the legacies of loyalty and filial piety, he comprehends the principles of all things. His competence was heard among the stargazers; his integrity was praised when he entered the censorate. Behold his towering bearing, a gentleman of honor; observe his upright virtue, a true servant of the crown. With the wide ribbon of authority, he spread the ruler's grace across the southern lands; with the imperial decree, he gathered the people's songs from western seas. Public opinion, moved by his merit, called him a man of repute. Testing him in high office, he leaped directly to the third rank. In the year of Sinmyo, bearing the axe of command at the frontier, when the barbarian hordes drew their bowstrings and raided the border, he alone defended the lonely fortress, directing all forces. Though assault came swiftly from without, his defense moved like divine spirit. With merely two thousand soldiers, employing cunning strategy, he battled the enemy for seventy days, his tactics inexhaustible. At last the invaders, exhausted, withdrew their siege. Yet considering the welfare of ten thousand people, two nations found peace. Fearing the enemy's dread of your prowess, we sent you to distant Flower County; remembering your deeds that eclipse the world, we recalled you to the celestial platform. Soon you were raised to the inner councils, then elevated to the highest administrative posts. Though we have entrusted you with great affairs, our heart remains unsatisfied. Therefore, let the Dragon Pool ministry place you to balance all affairs, and the Tiger Battalion train its armed forces under your hand. We grant you the position of Grand Mentor, adding further honor to your rank. We hereby appoint you Minister of the Right in the Chancellery, with authority over the Ministry of War and Preceptor of the Heir Apparent. All other posts remain as before.

    Official Lee Tzu-sung possesses a commanding presence and penetrating mind. With hands like lightning and heart like the divine pearl, he roamed freely in his youth, soaring in the dust of imperial carriages, swiftly ascending to high station. Inheriting his father's illustrious ways, as provincial governor he maintained principles pure as water; possessing the true nature of a general, he excels beyond fortress walls. He has mastered the secret stratagems of war and excels in the arts of brush and ink. The more soldiers he commands, the better his mastery—is this not the noble vision of a true patriot? Yet at times he seeks refuge in Chan Buddhism—the elegant refinement of one intoxicated with immortality. When a powerful neighbor invaded with hostile forces, joining other generals in expedition, the enemy made a desperate charge upon the road, and he alone met the sharpest assault. A flying arrow pierced his arm, blood streaming with the whip, yet drawing out the shaft, he advanced with unwavering composure, taking up spear and sword once more. Through his valor, all our forces were preserved. When barbarian envoys came as guests, they recognized his heroic visage among our assembled officials.

    Again, when we dispatched forces against the remnants of the Yellow Turban rebels, he wielded the crimson banner near the capital. Not long after the southward migration, some hearts wavered with uncertainty, and in the eastern city a faction of rebels gathered numbering tens of thousands. You, asking no delay for orders, hastened day and night across the roads. Though our forces were few and weak, your wisdom commanded perfectly; the rebels, arriving suddenly, fled of their own accord. Corpses lay scattered across a hundred li from a single proclamation. Thus did you ease our anxieties in this time of trial and restore stability to our trembling realm. We bestowed upon you the honor of the Privy Council and again entrusted you with the office of the Censorate. Remembering your extraordinary service, we wished to grant honors beyond measure, yet restraint held us back. Now we exchange your old rank for silver-blue insignia and grant you new gold-purple robes. Let you take seat in the central axis of power and hold sway over the ministry of territories. We hereby appoint you Grand Master of Purple Gold, Counselor-in-Chief over the Ministry of Household, and Grand Protector of the Heir Apparent.

    Official Song Sun possesses unwavering loyalty and upright character, with splendid beard and dignified bearing. His wise words and virtuous deeds have long served as model for many scholars; his vast learning and broad knowledge have earned him renown as a great sage. His brush and documents follow the orthodox transmission; already he showed signs of reaching the highest councils. Early he took his place among the censors, then was entrusted with provincial oversight. Skillful in administrative affairs, he graces them with classical learning. Possessed of calm and weighty bearing, he rose in the censorate; known for fair and balanced judgment, he was appointed to the civil service ministry. When dispatched to govern a major province, his teachings of benevolence illuminated the southern lands; entering the imperial academy, his influence extended through the corridors of power. In his position as Right Minister, the threads of governance were drawn taut, and the barbarians dared not approach. He held the seals of authority in that luminous seat, advancing and retiring with perfect timing, his virtue growing ever more manifest.

    When the court first moved south and hearts grew restless, he toured and pacified the regions. After the suppression of rebellion, when the people's livelihood was uncertain, he governed the eastern capital, preserving their welfare. He bore full responsibility for the treasury while simultaneously holding office at the secretariat, managing with red and black brush the registers of the military, his dignity upright before the throne. Thus did we recognize his great capacities, and elevating his rank in the central ministry made him our instrument for great works. Why should we be bound by ordinary precedent in showing such exceptional favor? We grant him the purple-gold insignia and raise him to the position of chief minister. As judge of the Board of Rites, let him establish the protocols of the five ceremonies; in editing the imperial records, let him illuminate the laws of ages past. In the Hall of Excellence he shall counsel us, and in the heir's residence he shall nurture the crown prince. We hereby appoint you Grand Master of Purple Gold, Counselor-in-Chief, Academician of the집현전, Historian of the Realm, Judge of the Ministry of Rites, and Lesser Mentor of the Heir Apparent.

    Official Im Kyong-suk possesses clarity and refinement, gentleness and respectfulness. Born of a family of ministers, he naturally knew the ways of propriety; raised in the household of chancellors, he transcended the habits of luxury. He holds to cultural refinement without pedantry, and masters the codes of government with deep knowledge of ancient and modern practice. Since his youth he ascended to court with sincere devotion to the ruler. Beneath the shade of the green parasol tree he rode repeatedly in the procession of royal teaching; before the purple tower he twice held the brush of imperial record. He rose to the important post of judge of flowers, advanced to the pure ranks of the spring season. In the Hall of Records he refined the chronicles with precision like human features; in the Eastern Corridor he displayed literary grace like silken patterns. Recently he ascended from the position of Left Minister to the Central Secretariat. Taking charge of the imperial scribal office, he overlooked no capable talent; composing treaties with foreign powers, he brought peace to distant borders. All proclaimed him a worthy minister, and we too recognized him as an ornament to the realm.

    Blessing accumulated from ancestors has descended upon his posterity. For four generations his family has held high office, spreading pure influence far and wide. His contemporary relatives all occupy important posts. He treads the righteous path without following base customs; dwelling in the secular world, he has gained insight into profound truths. His integrity grows ever higher though his years are yet not many. We must secure such worthy counsel to establish lasting peace today. Therefore we write this proclamation of honor and grant the gold seal of favor. Entering the hall of state council, he shall rely upon the depth of his learning; in selecting personnel for office, he shall depend upon his fair judgment in evaluation. Let him support and nurture the spring decrees, and administer well the winter offices. We hereby appoint you Grand Master of Purple Gold, Minister of State in the Hall of Governance, Minister of Personnel, Judge of the Ministry of Works, and Lesser Mentor of the Heir Apparent. All other posts remain as before.

    Alas, to find a worthy ruler is truly difficult, and to establish a capable minister is no easy task. To open one's heart and await counsel from you is our responsibility; to speak only when the way requires it is what we expect of you. Together let us bring forth the great peace, leaving words of lasting meaning for ages to come.
  footnotes:
    - 'The ''wide ribbon of authority'' refers to the badge of high office, from the Han historical records: ''With the ribbon of office one guards the outer lands.'''
    - The 'imperial decree' (尺一書) refers to official proclamations, called 'foot-and-inch documents' because they were written on wooden tablets of standardized length during the Han dynasty.
    - The transmission of 'orthodox learning' (衣鉢) draws on the Buddhist tradition wherein a master's robes and begging bowl pass to his successor, here signifying the continuity of scholarly authority.
    - The reference to 'teachings beneath the parasol tree' alludes to the Zhou dynasty governor Shao Gong, whose virtuous conduct beneath a sweet-pear tree earned such reverence that the people protected the tree itself as a memorial to his grace.
